WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:10.240
Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, this is Esther's Keith Orville bringing you

00:10.240 --> 00:16.140
the first in a series of television programs from the nation's capital, where we will

00:16.140 --> 00:21.760
review from time to time the Seedings in Congress and happenings of importance are going

00:21.760 --> 00:22.760
on in Washington.

00:22.760 --> 00:27.440
Last year we did this for five minutes once a week.

00:27.440 --> 00:31.880
This year in order to have more depth in the news and be able to have more distinguished

00:31.880 --> 00:34.880
guests on the program we are going to take 15 minutes.

00:34.880 --> 00:39.600
Now, I certainly appreciate the station carrying this program as a public service.

00:39.600 --> 00:45.320
I will appreciate you writing me in a suggestions about the program so that we can make it more

00:45.320 --> 00:46.960
useful and more informative.

00:46.960 --> 00:55.560
Today, we are highly honored to have on our next program or be four weeks from today.

00:55.560 --> 01:00.320
Today we are highly honored to have with us the new majority leader, the Democratic

01:00.320 --> 01:03.640
leader of the United States Senate.

01:03.640 --> 01:09.680
We had a able and efficient leader in Senator Lyndon B. Johnson for the past eight or

01:09.680 --> 01:10.680
nine years.

01:10.680 --> 01:16.240
Senator Johnson has been elevated to the vice presidency, as all of you know.

01:16.240 --> 01:22.120
And succeeding him is the distinguished senator from Montana, Mike Mansfield.

01:22.120 --> 01:23.440
I think it's certainly good to have you.

01:23.440 --> 01:28.280
You were elected by unanimous vote of all of the Democratic senators.

01:28.280 --> 01:32.240
We thank you for your efficient able, that you will carry out the program for the good

01:32.240 --> 01:33.240
of the people.

01:33.240 --> 01:38.600
And I want you to say introduce you to the people of Tennessee.

01:38.600 --> 01:43.160
Well, as to say, I only hope that I can live up to the high hopes, the high expectations

01:43.160 --> 01:47.280
that you and my other colleagues have placed in me.

01:47.280 --> 01:52.840
I have no illusions about the job, but I'm depending upon people like you and others to help

01:52.840 --> 01:54.720
me over the rough spots.

01:54.720 --> 02:01.640
We'll do our best collectively to reinforce the Kennedy program and to try and get this

02:01.640 --> 02:06.400
country back on an even keel and to bring some stability in the field of foreign relations.

02:06.400 --> 02:09.160
Well, Mike, you've been our very effective whip.

02:09.160 --> 02:12.400
That's the second in command for a number of years.

02:12.400 --> 02:17.880
We all know of your ability, your sincerity, your great integrity, and your forward-looking

02:17.880 --> 02:23.480
ideas about what's good for our nation and what's good for our best chance of having peace

02:23.480 --> 02:25.120
in the world.

02:25.120 --> 02:30.000
And you can certainly count on all of us to help you in every way that we possibly can.

02:30.000 --> 02:35.120
Incidentally, folks, Senator Mansfield is no stranger to Tennessee.

02:35.120 --> 02:43.200
We've served in a house of representatives from 1943 until I left in 1948, and then

02:43.200 --> 02:48.960
you came to the Senate in 1950, I believe, Mike.

02:48.960 --> 02:54.800
Back in 1954, when I was running for my second term in the United States Senate, Senator

02:54.800 --> 03:00.160
Mansfield was good enough to come down to Cookville, Tennessee, where he made the opening speech

03:00.160 --> 03:02.560
in my campaign during that year.

03:02.560 --> 03:08.160
A lot of people in Nashville and Cookville remember you very pleasantly.

03:08.160 --> 03:09.160
You remember that occasion?

03:09.160 --> 03:15.160
Esther, I certainly do, and I remember the final speech that you ever made to.

03:15.160 --> 03:19.160
Well, the reason was because it was one of the nicest groups I've ever faced.

03:19.160 --> 03:24.600
But you know, I want to go back to Tennessee someday to spend some time in the mountains and

03:24.600 --> 03:29.440
the western part of your state to look over the TVA and see the benefits it's brought to

03:29.440 --> 03:30.440
your people.

03:30.440 --> 03:35.720
And incidentally, you know there's a great deal of similarity between Montana and Tennessee.

03:35.720 --> 03:43.040
We have mountains, we have dams, we have rivers that need controlling, and you may be surprised.

03:43.040 --> 03:46.520
Everybody thinks that people from Tennessee always migrate to Texas, but we have a good

03:46.520 --> 03:51.040
many Tennessee and South Montana, and I'm happy to say they're a good demifact.

03:51.040 --> 03:52.040
Well, that's right, Mike.

03:52.040 --> 03:56.560
I was out there during the last campaign, and I saw a lot of them serve at the Tour de Moles

03:56.560 --> 03:57.560
in the Vaux-Ovoat right.

03:57.560 --> 04:01.520
We want you to come back because we both of our states are developing.

04:01.520 --> 04:07.080
We have great plans for the future, and we want you to bring Maureen down sometime, and

04:07.080 --> 04:13.560
the session is not so pectic and enjoy our mountains, the TVA and our people.

04:13.560 --> 04:17.560
Well, Mike, what's the program?

04:17.560 --> 04:23.520
First let's say, talk about the members of the cabinet and the official family that President

04:23.520 --> 04:26.440
of that kind of he has designated.

04:26.440 --> 04:30.840
I think that he has a fine team in the field with foreign affairs.

04:30.840 --> 04:36.000
I think he has experienced people, and I think he's getting a well all-around group of

04:36.000 --> 04:40.360
people to carry a part of his new frontier program.

04:40.360 --> 04:41.840
What is your feeling about it?

04:41.840 --> 04:43.440
I agree with you, Estes.

04:43.440 --> 04:48.240
I think that he's made a wonderful set of selections so far.

04:48.240 --> 04:52.920
It is anticipated that beginning very shortly, the appropriate committees in the Senate will

04:52.920 --> 04:58.200
start hearings on these nominees so that we can bring them to the floor of the Senate

04:58.200 --> 05:01.920
shortly after the inaugural for confirmation.

05:01.920 --> 05:06.560
And after that, we will, of course, expect the committees likewise to start hearings before

05:06.560 --> 05:12.840
the inauguration on the various legislative proposals, which President-elect Kennedy has

05:12.840 --> 05:15.920
announced during the course of his campaign and since.

05:15.920 --> 05:22.440
Mike, as much as he has picked good people in, and as much as the Senate always respects

05:22.440 --> 05:28.240
the rise in the desire of the President to have the people that he wants to help him,

05:28.240 --> 05:32.480
I wouldn't anticipate any trouble on any confirmation of any of the cabinet members

05:32.480 --> 05:33.480
that you've...

05:33.480 --> 05:41.180
No, I dare say that all of them will be approved fairly expeditiously, and I look for

05:41.180 --> 05:45.980
little friction, little argument, and fairly speedy consideration and approval.

05:45.980 --> 05:51.820
Mike, I've been telling everybody that I thought there were so many problems in the world,

05:51.820 --> 05:58.400
both domestically with unemployment and difficulties we're having here at home as well as many

05:58.400 --> 06:00.980
tactic problems and international affairs.

06:00.980 --> 06:06.700
I thought we would have very good teamwork both among the insiports, the Democrats are

06:06.700 --> 06:11.740
concerned, and insofar as the Republicans are concerned, at least far as considerable

06:11.740 --> 06:14.060
period of time, a good honeymoon with...

06:14.060 --> 06:15.540
Do you think that will be true?

06:15.540 --> 06:20.860
Yes, I think so, especially in the field of foreign policy, I believe that both parties

06:20.860 --> 06:26.300
will place the interest of the country ahead of the interest of their particular parties.

06:26.300 --> 06:32.220
I think even in the field of domestic affairs that will not feed the friction, which

06:32.220 --> 06:38.380
are great many anticipate because many Republicans will vote for these programs and do so all

06:38.380 --> 06:42.780
the more willingly because they are now not under pressure from the White House to vote

06:42.780 --> 06:46.100
the way the White House wants them to.

06:46.100 --> 06:50.660
So I look forward to a period of harmony and unity.

06:50.660 --> 06:54.620
There may be a few squabbles here and there, but it wouldn't be a Senate or a Democratic

06:54.620 --> 06:57.420
party if we didn't have these squabbles occasionally.

06:57.420 --> 07:03.260
I anticipate that we'll carry through the President's program in fairly good fashion,

07:03.260 --> 07:08.740
and I would hope that when this session of the Congress is concluded, we would be judged

07:08.740 --> 07:12.900
not under quantity of the legislation which we passed, but rather the quality.

07:12.900 --> 07:17.220
Well, that's what we all hope for and let's hope the honeymoon lasts as long as possible

07:17.220 --> 07:22.780
and we can get the President's program over and get some things done for the people and

07:22.780 --> 07:25.220
improve our situation in the world.

07:25.220 --> 07:31.860
On our Mr. Majority Leader, Mike, we are now engaged in a fight about the amendment of

07:31.860 --> 07:39.900
rule 22, which is the, as all of you know, is the rule about the termination of the

07:39.900 --> 07:43.780
date and preventing lengthy filibusters.

07:43.780 --> 07:45.580
What is the situation about that?

07:45.580 --> 07:48.300
Are we going to be able to get that behind us pretty soon?

07:48.300 --> 07:49.980
I would hope so, Estes.

07:49.980 --> 07:54.860
I would imagine that there will be a motion to table or move the previous question and

07:54.860 --> 07:56.660
do time.

07:56.660 --> 08:01.700
That will bring this matter to a head and then we will be able to get on to the business

08:01.700 --> 08:04.300
of the President's program.

08:04.300 --> 08:09.220
You know, I think people ought to recognize the fact that while there is a need for some

08:09.220 --> 08:16.060
reform in rule 22, that the important thing now is to get the President's program underway.

08:16.060 --> 08:23.060
Then, confesses a great many facets in the field of our domestic economy, housing,

08:23.060 --> 08:26.740
for example, which is in a terrible slump at the present time and which will do much

08:26.740 --> 08:29.820
to create employment for our people.

08:29.820 --> 08:33.700
The depressed area is, and I'm sure you have some of them down in your state as I have

08:33.700 --> 08:34.700
in mind.

08:34.700 --> 08:38.580
Mike, on that subject, depressed areas, we are getting more letters about that than most

08:38.580 --> 08:39.820
in the other subject.

08:39.820 --> 08:46.340
We have some 76 communities where they do have severe unemployment, particularly in

08:46.340 --> 08:52.980
cool mining sections like in Marians, the Quatsy and Grondi County where the coal is running

08:52.980 --> 08:58.060
out and it's expensive to manage it and we have some very bad situations so that bill

08:58.060 --> 09:02.020
is greatly needed in many parts of Tennessee as it is elsewhere.

09:02.020 --> 09:06.140
Do you think, of course, we passed a bill one time in Congress and you got vetoed as

09:06.140 --> 09:07.140
that?

09:07.140 --> 09:08.140
That's right, Paul.

09:08.140 --> 09:11.900
But now we have a President who will not be to a bill of that kind and I think we can

09:11.900 --> 09:16.220
pass the bill more in keeping with the realities of the situation.

09:16.220 --> 09:22.900
And Mike, about unemployment, unemployment is a pretty high peak.

09:22.900 --> 09:28.620
And what is your feeling about the best thing we can do in the most expeditious land to

09:28.620 --> 09:31.220
try to enable people to get back to work properly?

09:31.220 --> 09:38.100
Well, I think we ought to engage upon the President's program, aged depressed areas, both

09:38.100 --> 09:44.140
rural and urban, a housing program which will spur the construction industry and give

09:44.140 --> 09:50.700
sustenance to our people, aid to education, raising the minimum wage, all these are important

09:50.700 --> 09:55.620
and all of them are necessary because if my information is correct by about the first

09:55.620 --> 10:01.860
of February, we will have something on the order of five million, perhaps more unemployed.

10:01.860 --> 10:06.820
Now this has been referred to during the course of the late campaign as a quote, pause,

10:06.820 --> 10:09.180
unquote, in our economy.

10:09.180 --> 10:11.540
I hope it is not the pause that he presses.

10:11.540 --> 10:15.900
It is certainly something which calls for action with a man like Kennedy in the White House.

10:15.900 --> 10:21.260
Action will be taken to try and alleviate the situations in what you, in these areas

10:21.260 --> 10:26.860
you referred to, sometimes known as pockets of poverty, so that men and women able and

10:26.860 --> 10:33.140
willing will have the opportunity and the right to work and achieve a decent livelihood.

10:33.140 --> 10:41.300
Well, Mike, I always heard that I feel that a good housing program, and we had two vetoed

10:41.300 --> 10:47.140
last year and we finally got through a very, very watered-down housing program which is

10:47.140 --> 10:48.140
not adequate at all.

10:48.140 --> 10:53.740
But do more to spur and to increase employment immediately than almost anything else, not

10:53.740 --> 11:00.260
only in the timber industry and among construction workers, but also in the factories where they

11:00.260 --> 11:04.780
make frigidaires, stoves, and cuters and furnaces.

11:04.780 --> 11:07.660
So I imagine that will be how on the priority list.

11:07.660 --> 11:11.740
It will indeed, and what you said is correct because it goes far beyond the building of a

11:11.740 --> 11:16.880
house that affects so many other fields of economic endeavor, that what it does is create

11:16.880 --> 11:20.900
employment as it goes along and I think we ought to do something to overcome the terrible

11:20.900 --> 11:23.460
slump and housing evident this past year.

11:23.460 --> 11:28.380
And Mike and Montana, you are interested in the development of the harnessing of the

11:28.380 --> 11:32.500
Columbia and the Missouri River and other rivers.

11:32.500 --> 11:36.980
We in Tennessee, of course, are very proud of the Tennessee Valley Authority and for the

11:36.980 --> 11:42.660
information of all you've got folks as Senator and Mansfield, both as a Congressman and

11:42.660 --> 11:48.420
as a Senator, has always been a power strength for the Tennessee Valley Authority to protect

11:48.420 --> 11:53.500
it, to Father It and so we feel madigued on that score that he is the majority leader.

11:53.500 --> 11:57.700
Well, let's just let me tell you this, that it was because of your constant and unfailing

11:57.700 --> 12:03.660
championship of the TVA that you were so easily able to convert so many of us to cause

12:03.660 --> 12:05.060
and to keep us under your banner.

12:05.060 --> 12:09.260
Well, of course, Senator Gore and I are very much for the TVA, but that's how you feel

12:09.260 --> 12:11.820
otherwise you wouldn't have been so enthusiastic, Mike.

12:11.820 --> 12:17.540
But resource development and building up our country will be a vital part of the program

12:17.540 --> 12:20.420
of the President and of the Congress.

12:20.420 --> 12:22.420
Very vital part.

12:22.420 --> 12:27.660
In the minute or two remaining, Mike, how about the development of our greats national

12:27.660 --> 12:28.660
parts?

12:28.660 --> 12:35.260
You have a, we have a smokey mountain national part and you have Yellowstone and glacier.

12:35.260 --> 12:39.460
Glacier and others, we need to give them more attention, much is that.

12:39.460 --> 12:40.460
Yes indeed.

12:40.460 --> 12:45.340
Considering more attention, I would hope that the Mission 66 program would be accentuated,

12:45.340 --> 12:48.980
that the amounts of money which must be spent would be put into our parts because they

12:48.980 --> 12:54.380
do represent an investment in which all America can participate and I think that if we do

12:54.380 --> 12:59.700
not undertake a program of this kind that we will be the losers and the results may well

12:59.700 --> 13:02.500
be that the parts will be carried still further.

13:02.500 --> 13:08.020
Well, Mike, we don't have much time remaining, but we've seen that you've been have a package

13:08.020 --> 13:11.980
for the reform of the electoral college of which I'm interested to.

13:11.980 --> 13:13.980
Will that be part of the program?

13:13.980 --> 13:18.660
No, that is my own personal idea, but I think something ought to be done about the electoral

13:18.660 --> 13:22.180
college, something ought to be done about the length and the cost of campaigns and something

13:22.180 --> 13:25.740
ought to be done about the interregnum between the election and the title of president takes

13:25.740 --> 13:26.740
over.

13:26.740 --> 13:29.340
Well, I certainly agree with you and I have been working on that myself as you know for

13:29.340 --> 13:30.340
a number of years.

13:30.340 --> 13:32.860
Well, thank you very much, Senator Manstale.

13:32.860 --> 13:36.980
You are a great leader and a great friend of the people of this nation and of Tennessee.

13:36.980 --> 13:37.980
Asters is a pleasure.

13:37.980 --> 13:41.660
And ladies and gentlemen, until four weeks from now, that's all.

13:41.660 --> 13:42.180
Thank you very much.

