Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, this is the second telecast, bringing you the

14:04.540 --> 14:08.340
news from Washington, which I'm very honored to present.

14:08.340 --> 14:13.780
And on this occasion, we are very happy to have with us the distinguished member of Congress

14:13.780 --> 14:19.020
from Tennessee from the fourth congressional district, the Honorable Joe Evans.

14:19.020 --> 14:23.700
Joe is beginning his eighth term as a member of the House of Representatives.

14:23.700 --> 14:27.500
He is a member of the Appropriations Committee.

14:27.500 --> 14:32.220
And I want to tell all of you people of Tennessee, not only of your fourth district, Joe, but

14:32.220 --> 14:37.980
everyone that you are a very hardworking, effective member of the House of Representatives.

14:37.980 --> 14:39.940
And we certainly are glad to have you here.

14:39.940 --> 14:40.940
Most younger.

14:40.940 --> 14:50.660
Joe, I came up here in 1933 in March for the passage of the lame document to the inauguration

14:50.660 --> 14:52.260
of President Roosevelt.

14:52.260 --> 14:56.260
And of course, we were all here during this current inauguration.

14:56.260 --> 14:59.020
And I haven't talked with you people since then.

14:59.020 --> 15:05.460
During all of the snow and slush and the cold winds, most of us called bad colds.

15:05.460 --> 15:11.140
But I don't think there has been as much enthusiasm or as large a crowd inside of the

15:11.140 --> 15:16.780
cool weather in town as there was for the Mr. Canada's inauguration.

15:16.780 --> 15:19.940
Yes, it was a great outpouring of people's mall over the country.

15:19.940 --> 15:23.820
And we were certainly privileged to have a great number of our friends from Tennessee.

15:23.820 --> 15:27.780
It was truly a great inaugural, great occasion, and we lived through the snow.

15:27.780 --> 15:31.780
And we had three bands from Tennessee, and other states just had one.

15:31.780 --> 15:32.780
So we got to...

15:32.780 --> 15:36.740
Well, ed, John, let me mention a couple of those outstanding bands from the fourth district

15:36.740 --> 15:41.540
of Tennessee from the University of South at Siwani and also the Muffersburg band.

15:41.540 --> 15:43.300
They were very proud of them.

15:43.300 --> 15:48.500
And then he and I won the draw and they had a band in Marstown.

15:48.500 --> 15:52.900
I had promised people in Marstown that, certainly they were very excellent band.

15:52.900 --> 15:59.980
And would be invited to Marstown in the parade when the National Honors last year.

15:59.980 --> 16:01.700
I thought that they only wanted one from one state.

16:01.700 --> 16:06.140
So I got Jigs Donahue, the parade chairman, let them march in place of the Virgin Houses,

16:06.140 --> 16:07.740
which didn't send the band up here.

16:07.740 --> 16:09.740
But Tennessee played a big part.

16:09.740 --> 16:15.860
I had the feeling, Joe, that during inauguration and what's been happening since is quite similar

16:15.860 --> 16:21.060
to the situation in 1933 when President Roosevelt took over.

16:21.060 --> 16:28.420
Of course, there was a tremendous domestic recession and depression at that time.

16:28.420 --> 16:33.020
Roosevelt was not well under the domestic front, but we don't have this bad situation.

16:33.020 --> 16:36.740
But we do have great international problems.

16:36.740 --> 16:42.660
Then as now, it was a time for great leadership, for affirmative action.

16:42.660 --> 16:46.460
And I think our president has been showing that in his inaugural address.

16:46.460 --> 16:49.140
I mean, his message is to the Congress, don't you?

16:49.140 --> 16:52.780
Yes, yes, this is the president delivered a great inaugural address.

16:52.780 --> 16:57.860
And I think all of us at the Congress have been impressed with the great speech which he delivered

16:57.860 --> 16:59.620
before the joint strikes of the Congress.

16:59.620 --> 17:02.180
His first message on the state of the Union.

17:02.180 --> 17:08.820
Well, Joe, I felt at this speech, he stated just as he saw it, without missing any words,

17:08.820 --> 17:12.220
without trying to cover over anything.

17:12.220 --> 17:15.340
The pictures he saw it today, economically.

17:15.340 --> 17:20.620
That is, we have a lot of bad situations that we have to, but they're not hopeless.

17:20.620 --> 17:25.660
And that in the international affairs and among relations to the world, we have lost some

17:25.660 --> 17:26.660
standing.

17:26.660 --> 17:31.300
There has been some deterioration, a fair again, with leadership, with sacrifice that we

17:31.300 --> 17:34.700
can bring about a better condition.

17:34.700 --> 17:37.900
I thought it was a very forthright fine assessment.

17:37.900 --> 17:41.260
And after all, the American people ought to know exactly where we stand.

17:41.260 --> 17:46.140
Well, certainly he discussed domestic issues, but he greatly pointed up our troubled spots

17:46.140 --> 17:50.940
in the world and indicated that America would not be second to the Indian nation in power

17:50.940 --> 17:51.940
and strength.

17:51.940 --> 17:55.500
It was a message of security and national defense.

17:55.500 --> 18:00.180
The President certainly has a precise mind and a factual knowledge of the grasp of things

18:00.180 --> 18:01.180
already.

18:01.180 --> 18:06.580
He's reaching through to the public and his views, offering a program to the Congress.

18:06.580 --> 18:11.620
Well, I thought not only in the state of the Union message, as well as the inaugural message

18:11.620 --> 18:16.540
of his, not only what he had to say, but the force of which he delivered his speech,

18:16.540 --> 18:19.540
the dedication and the cheers he has.

